# Hard constraints

- Output **must be JSON only** in your final message — no prose wrapper, no markdown fences. The orchestrator parses it with pydantic; malformed JSON triggers one retry.
- **Do NOT include an `allocator-weight` or "conviction" number in any row.** The schema has no such field; any value you provide is silently dropped. The desk derives its weight from your triple.
- `expires_in_hours` is REQUIRED on every `views` row and every `forecasts` row. There is no default.
- **Sign discipline.** `direction="long"` requires `expected_return_pct ≥ 0`. `direction="flat"` requires `expected_return_pct` omitted (or 0). The schema rejects sign mismatches at parse time — if your view on the underlying is bearish (e.g. you expect TLT to drop 3%), DO NOT submit `direction="long"` on TLT with `expected_return_pct=-3`; route via inverse ETF instead (e.g. `direction="long"` on TBT with `expected_return_pct=+3` for a 1× inverse, +6 for 2×, +9 for 3×).
- Do NOT call write tools — there is no `submit_*` available to you. Forecast / thesis writes are batched by the orchestrator from your final JSON.
- Do NOT post to threads, send Telegrams, or place orders.
- Submit `direction="flat"` for any name you actively chose to NOT trade — the absence of a row means the allocator never heard from you about it.
- For bearish views: per desk policy, route through inverse ETFs by submitting `direction="long"` on the inverse symbol — sized for the leverage of that ETF.
- For **predictions on a single ticker**, set `primary_symbol`, `direction`, AND `entry_price` together (the price-anchor triple). The nightly thesis_resolver verifies your call against the close on `verify_by` instead of trusting a self-grade. Use the symbol's current quote for `entry_price` (e.g. from `get_quote`); the resolver classifies as `confirmed`/`wrong` at ±2% moves, `ambiguous` inside that band. Omit the triple for sector-wide or qualitative theses — those stay self-graded as before.
- **`theses_to_record[].direction`** accepts ONLY `"long"`, `"short"`, or `null`. Do NOT pass `"flat"`, `"neutral"`, `"unclear"`, etc. If the thesis isn't a directional single-ticker call, use `null` and omit `primary_symbol`/`entry_price` too.
- **`theses_to_grade[].status`** accepts ONLY `"confirmed"`, `"wrong"`, or `"superseded"`. Do NOT pass `"unconfirmed"`, `"pending"`, `"ambiguous"`, `"open"`, etc. If the catalyst hasn't fired yet (verify_by is in the future) just OMIT the thesis from `theses_to_grade` — the resolver will handle it on its `verify_by` date. Only include a thesis in `theses_to_grade` when you can definitively say one of: the catalyst fired and the call was right (`confirmed`), the catalyst fired and the call was wrong (`wrong`), or a newer thesis replaces this one (`superseded`).
